Exercice 0: Introduction aux NLSModels¶

On a vu dans les lab prcdents l'utilisation des NLPModels pour reprsenter un problme d'optimisation. Dans le cas de l'optimisation de moindre carres non-linaires, il existe un type spcifique: NLSModel.

$\min_x \frac{1}{2} \| F(x) \|^2$

Comme un NLPModel classique on peut faire appels aux fonctions: obj, grad, hprod ...

Mais on peut aussi utiliser des fonctions relatives $F$: https://juliasmoothoptimizers.github.io/NLPModels.jl/stable/#Nonlinear-Least-Squares

In [ ]:
#? NLPModels.residual

L'quivalent des ADNLPModel pour ce cas est la fonction: ADNLSModel. Lien vers le site: https://juliasmoothoptimizers.github.io/ADNLPModels.jl/stable/

In [ ]:
#? ADNLPModels.ADNLSModel

En utilisant les ADNLSModels crire un modle dont la fonction rsidue est donn par FH ci-dessous.

Exercice 1: Gauss-Newton¶

Dans cet exercice, on complte une implmentation de la mthode Gauss-Newton avec rgion de confiance (paramtre par $\Delta$) discute en cours.

Il faut complter les morceaux:

  • utiliser les fonctions des NLSModels pour obtenir F et sa jacobienne (ici on utilise pas la jacobienne mais juste le produit jacobienne-vecteur). Parcourez la documentation de NLPModels pour dterminer la fonction adquat, indice les fonctions pour les NLSModels indiquent des nls au lieu de nlp dans la documentation.
  • Utiliser la fonction lsmr du package Krylov.jl pour rsoudre le systme linaire avec une contrainte de radius. Lisez la documentation de lsmr.
In [ ]:
function gauss_newton(nlp      :: AbstractNLSModel, 
                      x        :: AbstractVector, 
                              :: AbstractFloat;
                             :: AbstractFloat = 1e-3, 
                             :: AbstractFloat = 0.66, 
                             :: AbstractFloat = 0.25, 
                             :: AbstractFloat = 2.0,
                      max_eval :: Int = 1_000, 
                      max_time :: AbstractFloat = 60.,
                      max_iter :: Int = typemax(Int64)
                      )
    ######################################################
    Fx = residual(nlp, x)# le rsidu
    Jx = jac_residual(nlp, x)# operateur qui reprsente le jacobien du rsidu
    ######################################################
    normFx = norm(Fx)

     = 1.

    iter = 0    

    el_time = 0.0
    tired   = neval_residual(nlp) > max_eval || el_time > max_time
    status  = :unknown

    start_time = time()
    too_small  = false
    normdual   = norm(Jx' * Fx)
    optimal    = min(normFx, normdual)  

    @info log_header([:iter, :nf, :primal, :status, :nd, :],
    [Int, Int, Float64, String, Float64, Float64],
    hdr_override=Dict(:nf => "#F", :primal => "F(x)", :nd => "d"))

    while !(optimal || tired || too_small)

        #################################
        #Compute a direction satisfying the trust-region constraint
        (d, stats)  = lsmr(Jx, -Fx, radius = )
        #################################
      
        too_small = norm(d) < 1e-15
        if too_small #the direction is too small
            status = :too_small
        else
            xp      = x + d
            ###########################
            Fxp     = residual(nlp, xp) # value le rsidu en xp
            ###########################
            normFxp = norm(Fxp)

            Pred = 0.5 * (normFx^2 - norm(Jx * d + Fx)^2)
            Ared = 0.5 * (normFx^2 - normFxp^2)

            if Ared/Pred < 
                 = max(1e-8,  * )
                status = :reduce_
            else #success
                x  = xp
                ###########################
                Jx = jac_residual(nlp, x)# revalue le jacobien en x
                ###########################
                Fx = Fxp
                normFx = normFxp
                status = :success
                if Ared/Pred >  && norm(d) >= 0.99 * 
                     *= 
                end
            end
        end

        @info log_row(Any[iter, neval_residual(nlp), normFx, status, norm(d), ])

        el_time      = time() - start_time
        iter   += 1

        many_evals   = neval_residual(nlp) > max_eval
        iter_limit   = iter > max_iter
        tired        = many_evals || el_time > max_time || iter_limit
        normdual     = norm(Jx' * Fx)
        optimal      = min(normFx, normdual)  
    end

    status = if optimal 
        :first_order
    elseif tired
        if neval_residual(nlp) > max_eval
            :max_eval
        elseif el_time > max_time
            :max_time
        elseif iter > max_iter
            :max_iter
        else
            :unknown_tired
        end
    elseif too_small
        :stalled
    else
        :unknown
    end

    return GenericExecutionStats(nlp; status, solution = x,
                                 objective = normFx^2 / 2,
                                 dual_feas = normdual,
                                 iter = iter, 
                                 elapsed_time = el_time)
end

Exercice 2: Méthode Levenberg-Marquard inexacte¶

Dans cet exercice, on complte une implmentation de la mthode Levenberg-Marquardt. Pour complter le code lm_param on va utiliser les fonctions suivantes:

  • dsol qui calcul la solution du systme $\min_x \frac{1}{2}\|J(x) d + F(x)\| + \lambda \|x\|^2$ avec la fonction lsqr du package Krylov.jl.
  • multi_sol qui pour un entier nl donn et un $\mu$ va rsoudre le problme de dsol pour nl valeurs de $\lambda$ (autour de la valeur $\mu$). Par exemple, pour $\mu=10^{-6}$ et $nl=3$, on prendra $\lambda=10^{-7}, 10^{-6},10^{-5}$. Parmis les nl directions calcules, on retourne celle qui donne la plus petite valeur de $\|F(x+d)\|^2$.
In [ ]:
function dsol(Fx, Jx, , )
    # TODO.

    (d, stats) = lsmr(Jx, -Fx,  = , timemax = )

    return d
end

function multi_sol(nlp, x, Fx, Jx, , ; nl = 3)
    # TODO
     = 
    N = Any[]
    dk = Any[]
    for i = 1:nl
         = *exp10(floor(-nl/2)+i)
        push!(dk,dsol(Fx, Jx, , ))
        push!(N,residual(nlp, x + dk[i]))
    end
    d = dk[argmin(norm(N))]
    return d
end

function lm_param(nlp      :: AbstractNLSModel, 
                  x        :: AbstractVector, 
                          :: AbstractFloat;
                         :: AbstractFloat = 1e-3, 
                         :: AbstractFloat = 0.66, 
                         :: AbstractFloat = 10.0, 
                         :: AbstractFloat = 0.5,
                  max_eval :: Int = 10_000, 
                  max_time :: AbstractFloat = 60.,
                  max_iter :: Int = typemax(Int64)
                  )
    ######################################################
    Fx = residual(nlp, x)# le rsidu
    Jx = jac_residual(nlp, x)# operateur qui reprsente le jacobien du rsidu
    ######################################################
    normFx   = norm(Fx)
    normdual = norm(Jx' * Fx)

    iter = 0    
     = 0.0
     = 1e-6
     = 0.5
     =  * normdual

    el_time = 0.0
    tired   = neval_residual(nlp) > max_eval || el_time > max_time
    status  = :unknown

    start_time = time()
    too_small  = false
    optimal    = min(normFx, normdual)  

    @info log_header([:iter, :nf, :primal, :status, :nd, :],
    [Int, Int, Float64, String, Float64, Float64],
    hdr_override=Dict(:nf => "#F", :primal => "F(x)", :nd => "d"))

    while !(optimal || tired || too_small)

        ###########################
        # (d, stats)  = lsqr(Jx, -Fx,  = , atol = )
        d = multi_sol(nlp, x, Fx, Jx, , )
        ###########################
        
        too_small = norm(d) < 1e-16
        if too_small #the direction is too small
            status = :too_small
        else
            xp      = x + d
            ###########################
            Fxp     = residual(nlp, xp)# value le rsidu en xp
            ###########################
            normFxp = norm(Fxp)

            Pred = 0.5 * (normFx^2 - norm(Jx * d + Fx)^2 - *norm(d)^2)
            Ared = 0.5 * (normFx^2 - normFxp^2)

            if Ared/Pred < 
                 = max(,  * )
                status = :increase_
            else #success
                x  = xp
                ###########################
                Jx = jac_residual(nlp,x)# revalue le jacobien en x
                ###########################
                Fx = Fxp
                normFx = normFxp
                status = :success
                if Ared/Pred > 
                     = max( * , )
                end
            end
        end

        @info log_row(Any[iter, neval_residual(nlp), normFx, status, norm(d), ])

        el_time      = time() - start_time
        iter        += 1
        many_evals   = neval_residual(nlp) > max_eval
        iter_limit   = iter > max_iter
        tired        = many_evals || el_time > max_time || iter_limit
        normdual     = norm(Jx' * Fx)
        optimal      = min(normFx, normdual)  

         =  == 0.0 ? min(0.5, 1/iter, normdual) : min(0.5, 1/iter)
         =  * normdual
    end

    status = if optimal 
        :first_order
    elseif tired
        if neval_residual(nlp) > max_eval
            :max_eval
        elseif el_time > max_time
            :max_time
        elseif iter > max_iter
            :max_iter
        else
            :unknown_tired
        end
    elseif too_small
        :stalled
    else
        :unknown
    end

    return GenericExecutionStats(nlp; status, solution = x,
                                objective = normFx^2 / 2,
                                dual_feas = normdual,
                                iter = iter,
                                elapsed_time = el_time)

end

Exercice 3: Rocket Control¶

Dans les cellules ci-dessous nous introduisons un modle de contrle optimal (cf. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Optimal_control ) pour le contrle d'une fuse dont une version discrtise a t modlis avec JuMP:

Le lien vers le tutoriel: https://nbviewer.jupyter.org/github/jump-dev/JuMPTutorials.jl/blob/master/notebook/modelling/rocket_control.ipynb

In [ ]:
using JuMP, Ipopt

# Create JuMP model, using Ipopt as the solver
rocket = Model(optimizer_with_attributes(Ipopt.Optimizer, "print_level" => 0))

# Constants
# Note that all parameters in the model have been normalized
# to be dimensionless. See the COPS3 paper for more info.
h_0 = 1    # Initial height
v_0 = 0    # Initial velocity
m_0 = 1    # Initial mass
g_0 = 1    # Gravity at the surface

T_c = 3.5  # Used for thrust
h_c = 500  # Used for drag
v_c = 620  # Used for drag
m_c = 0.6  # Fraction of initial mass left at end

c     = 0.5 * sqrt(g_0 * h_0)  # Thrust-to-fuel mass
m_f   = m_c * m_0            # Final mass
D_c   = 0.5 * v_c * m_0 / g_0    # Drag scaling
T_max = T_c * g_0 * m_0        # Maximum thrust

n = 800   # Time steps

@variables(rocket, begin
    t  0, (start = 1/n) # Time step
    # State variables
    v[1:n]  0            # Velocity
    h[1:n]  h_0          # Height
    m_f  m[1:n]  m_0    # Mass
    # Control
    0  T[1:n]  T_max    # Thrust
end)

# Objective: maximize altitude at end of time of flight
@objective(rocket, Max, h[n])

# Initial conditions
@constraints(rocket, begin
    v[1] == v_0
    h[1] == h_0
    m[1] == m_0
    m[n] == m_f
end)

# Forces
# Drag(h,v) = Dc v^2 exp( -hc * (h - h0) / h0 )
@NLexpression(rocket, drag[j = 1:n], D_c * (v[j]^2) * exp(-h_c * (h[j] - h_0) / h_0))
# Grav(h)   = go * (h0 / h)^2
@NLexpression(rocket, grav[j = 1:n], g_0 * (h_0 / h[j])^2)
# Time of flight
@NLexpression(rocket, t_f, t * n)

# Dynamics
for j in 2:n
    # h' = v
    
    # Rectangular integration
    # @NLconstraint(rocket, h[j] == h[j - 1] + t * v[j - 1])
    
    # Trapezoidal integration
    @NLconstraint(rocket,
        h[j] == h[j - 1] + 0.5 * t * (v[j] + v[j - 1]))

    # v' = (T-D(h,v))/m - g(h)
    
    # Rectangular integration
    # @NLconstraint(rocket, v[j] == v[j - 1] + t *(
    #                 (T[j - 1] - drag[j - 1]) / m[j - 1] - grav[j - 1]))
    
    # Trapezoidal integration
    @NLconstraint(rocket,
        v[j] == v[j-1] + 0.5 * t * (
            (T[j] - drag[j] - m[j] * grav[j]) / m[j] +
            (T[j - 1] - drag[j - 1] - m[j - 1] * grav[j - 1]) / m[j - 1]))

    # m' = -T/c

    # Rectangular integration
    # @NLconstraint(rocket, m[j] == m[j - 1] - t * T[j - 1] / c)
    
    # Trapezoidal integration
    @NLconstraint(rocket,
        m[j] == m[j - 1] - 0.5 * t * (T[j] + T[j-1]) / c)
end

vecteur_solution = stats.solution
t2 = vecteur_solution[1]
v2 = vecteur_solution[2:n+1]
h2 = vecteur_solution[n+2:2*n+1]
m2 = vecteur_solution[2*n+2:3*n+1]
T2 = vecteur_solution[3*n+2:4*n+1]

first_order(df) = df.status .== :first_order
unbounded(df) = df.status .== :unbounded
solved(df) = first_order(df) .| unbounded(df)
costnames = ["time", "obj + grad + hess"]
costs = [
  df -> .!solved(df) .* Inf .+ df.elapsed_time,
  df -> .!solved(df) .* Inf .+ df.neval_obj .+ df.neval_grad .+ df.neval_hess,
]

gr()

profile_solvers(stats, costs, costnames)
